Our framework provides a formal basis for understanding why physicists disagree about quantum interpretations:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Bohmian mechanics} implicitly privileges the Observer Frame $\mathcal{O}$ and seeks to extend it into the Cross-Dimensional Space $\mathcal{X}$ through the addition of hidden variables.
\item \textbf{Copenhagen interpretation} recognizes the necessity of both $\mathcal{O}$ and $\mathcal{I}$ frames but does not postulate a complete description in $\mathcal{X}$.
\item \textbf{Many-worlds interpretation} attempts to model $\mathcal{X}$ directly through the universal wavefunction, sacrificing aspects of the Individual Frame $\mathcal{I}$.
\item \textbf{QBism} privileges the Individual Frame $\mathcal{I}$ and views the Observer Frame $\mathcal{O}$ as derived from experiential beliefs.
\end{itemize}
\begin{theorem}[Necessity of Complete Framework]
A complete physical theory must incorporate all three spaces: the objective Observer Frame $\mathcal{O}$, the Cross-Dimensional Space $\mathcal{X}$, and the subjective Individual Frame $\mathcal{I}$. Any attempt to reduce physics to a single perspective necessarily creates paradoxes when confronting quantum phenomena.
\end{theorem}
