We have presented a formal framework for reconciling deterministic and indeterministic perspectives in quantum mechanics through the OXI formalism. By recognizing that quantum paradoxes arise from projecting higher-dimensional phenomena onto limited frames of reference, we provide a mathematical foundation for understanding why different interpretations arise and how they might be reconciled.
The key insight of our approach is that the universe exists simultaneously as an objective reality, a subjective experience, and a higher-dimensional structure that transcends both. The apparent conflicts between determinism and indeterminism reflect the incompleteness of any single perspective rather than fundamental contradictions in reality itself.
This framework opens new avenues for research in quantum foundations by suggesting that the search for a single, correct interpretation of quantum mechanics may be misguided. Instead, a complete understanding requires acknowledging the complementary nature of different perspectives and the limitations inherent in any projection from the complete cross-dimensional description.
