\section{The Light Clock Demonstration: Numerical Example of the Vantage Tilt}

In this section, we provide a concrete numerical example to demonstrate how our OXI framework naturally explains the apparent paradoxes of special relativity through the geometric concept of vantage tilt. We will work with a classic light clock scenario where one observer is moving relative to another at a high velocity, and show how the vantage illusions of time dilation and length contraction emerge naturally from the projection of higher-dimensional geometry onto limited perspective frames.

\subsection{Setup: The Light Clock Scenario}

Consider the classic light clock thought experiment with the following parameters:

\begin{itemize}
\item Embankment observer (Observer 1) is stationary in frame $K$.
\item Train observer (Observer 2) is moving at velocity $v = 0.8c$ relative to the embankment in frame $K'$.
\item Each observer has a light clock consisting of two mirrors separated by a distance $L = 1$ light-second in their rest frame.
\item Light bounces vertically between the mirrors, perpendicular to the direction of motion.
\end{itemize}

In standard special relativity, each observer sees the other's clock running slow due to time dilation, with the factor:
\begin{equation}
\gamma = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\beta^2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-0.8^2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-0.64}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{0.36}} = \frac{1}{0.6} = 1.6667
\end{equation}

\subsection{The OXI Framework Embedding}

In our framework, we embed this scenario in a 3D manifold with coordinates $\{\tau, x, t_x\}$, where:
\begin{itemize}
\item $\tau$ = universal turn dimension (replaces standard "time" concept)
\item $x$ = spatial coordinate in the direction of motion
\item $t_x$ = internal time dimension paired with $x$
\end{itemize}

The embankment observer (Observer 1) embeds their reference frame as:
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\tau = t \\
t_x = 0 \\
x = x
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

The train observer (Observer 2) embeds their reference frame with a tilt angle $\alpha = \arctan(\beta) = \arctan(0.8) \approx 38.66^\circ$ in the $(\tau, t_x)$ plane:
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\tau = \cos\alpha \cdot t' + \sin\alpha \cdot \beta x' \\
t_x = -\sin\alpha \cdot t' + \cos\alpha \cdot \beta x' \\
x = x'
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

Substituting our values:
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\tau = 0.7808 \cdot t' + 0.6247 \cdot 0.8 x' \\
t_x = -0.6247 \cdot t' + 0.7808 \cdot 0.8 x' \\
x = x'
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

Which simplifies to:
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\tau = 0.7808 \cdot t' + 0.4997 \cdot x' \\
t_x = -0.6247 \cdot t' + 0.6247 \cdot x' \\
x = x'
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

